  <section id="plugin">
    <title>Configuring plugins</title>
    <p>
      After opening the Preferences Dialog, you will find a list of all available plugins, with corresponding checkboxes,
      under the "Plugins" tab. Selecting a checkbox will activate the related plugin; analogously, unselecting a checkbox
      will inactivate it. Only active plugins can be accessed via <app>Accerciser</app>'s interface.
    </p>
    <p>
      Right-clicking a specific plugin opens a dialog with existing layout options, such as "Top Panel" and "Bottom Panel".
      Clicking a layout option will set it as default for the right-clicked plugin. This dialog also has a "New view" option,
      where you can create another layout for plugins. The created layout will be set as default for the right-clicked plugin.
    </p>
    <note style="tip">
      <p>
        You may bypass the Preferences dialog by using drag and drop to move a plugin from a layout to another. Dragging a plugin
        either to the bottom or to the top panel will move it. Dragging a plugin to the desktop will create a new plugin layout 
        and set it as default for the plugin.
      </p>
    </note>
  </section>
  <section id="global_hotkey">
    <title>Configuring global hotkeys</title>
    <p>
      Some elements in <app>Accerciser</app> may enable certain functionalities via hotkeys. An example is the 
      <link xref="quick_select_plugin">Quick Select Plugin</link>. The hotkey combination for each functionality
      could be changed via the Preferences dialog, under the "Global Hotkeys" tab. Under this tab, you will find
      a list of all available hotkey features with corresponding checkboxes for keys <key>ctrl</key>, <key>alt</key>,
      and <key>shift</key>. Selecting a checkbox will add the related key to the hotkey; analogously, unselecting
      a checkbox will remove it from the hotkey. 
    </p>
   </section>
   <section id="highlighting">
     <title>Configuring widget's highlighting</title>
     <p>
       Some of <app>Accerciser</app>'s elements, such as the global hotkey <key>ctrl</key>+<key>alt</key>+<key>/</key>,
       highlight a specific widget in a target application. The highlighting duration, border color, and fill color can
       be customized via the Preferences dialog, under the "Highlighting" tab.
     </p>
   </section>
